WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.840
Hi everybody, welcome to the Data Science Hangout. I'm sure we'll have quite a few people

00:00:10.840 --> 00:00:16.600
joining in in the next few minutes here too. But if you're joining for the first time,

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:22.400
it's great to meet you. I'm Rachel. If this is your first Hangout, this is an open space

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:28.480
for the whole data science community to connect and chat about data science leadership, questions

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:34.080
you're facing, and what's really going on in the world of data science. These sessions

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:40.200
are recorded and shared to YouTube as well as the rstudio Data Science Hangout site.

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:46.279
So you can always go back and rewatch to find helpful resources or share with others. I'll

00:00:46.279 --> 00:00:50.880
say this up front because I always forget this. We also have a LinkedIn group for the

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:56.599
Hangout too. So if you ever want to continue a certain discussion or see a brief summary

00:00:56.599 --> 00:01:02.959
of a topic brought up each week, you can join that group. I'll share it in just a second

00:01:02.959 --> 00:01:10.839
so I don't pause here. But we always want to create spaces where everybody can participate

00:01:10.839 --> 00:01:16.839
and we can hear from everyone. So there's three ways you can ask questions today. You

00:01:16.839 --> 00:01:21.760
can jump in by raising your hand on Zoom and I'll just call on you. You can put questions

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:26.279
in the Zoom chat and feel free to just put a little star next to it if you want me to

00:01:26.279 --> 00:01:32.320
read it out loud instead. Or I can call on you to introduce yourself and ask. But we

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:37.760
also have a Slido link that Hannah will share in just a second here in the chat where you

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:44.000
can ask questions anonymously too. So this is all for you and all the questions are audience

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.760
led. So just like to reiterate, we love to hear from everyone, no matter your level of

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:55.839
experience or area of work. But today, I'm so happy to be joined by my co-host, Travis

00:01:55.839 --> 00:02:03.199
Gerk. Travis is Director of Data Science at the Prostate Cancer Clinical Trials Consortium.

00:02:03.199 --> 00:02:08.600
That's a hard one to say. But Travis, I'd love to turn it over to you and have you just

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:12.759
introduce yourself and maybe share a little bit about the work that you do.

00:02:12.759 --> 00:02:18.360
Yeah, sure. So hi, I'm Travis. Thanks so much for having me. This is really great. I've

00:02:18.399 --> 00:02:23.199
been on a couple of Hangouts and they're always fun. So right, as Rachel said, I'm Director

00:02:23.199 --> 00:02:27.119
of Data Science at the Prostate Cancer Clinical Trials Consortium, which yes, it is a

00:02:27.119 --> 00:02:32.720
mouthful. An acronym might be even more tricky, PCCTC. Try saying that five times fast.

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:37.399
But whatever the case of you, we're sort of a we're a CRO, so a clinical research

00:02:37.399 --> 00:02:45.559
organization, meaning that we facilitate the work of clinical trials from end to end for

00:02:45.559 --> 00:02:51.240
often pharmaceutical sponsors or sometimes so-called independent investigator initiated

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:57.039
trials, which will be maybe physician scientists who've initiated a trial at their at their

00:02:57.039 --> 00:03:03.399
site at their hospital. And we have a we're sort of a boutique CRO in the sense we mostly

00:03:03.399 --> 00:03:08.839
do prostate cancer oncology work. So right now we're running about a quarter of all early

00:03:08.839 --> 00:03:14.160
phase clinical trials in late stage prostate cancer in the US. And we have a few global

00:03:14.199 --> 00:03:20.240
studies as well. So it's good. We do, as I said, we kind of collect all the data at the

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:24.000
sites. We help the sites launch the trial. And then once the data starts rolling in,

00:03:24.279 --> 00:03:27.600
that's when the data science team takes over. They do a lot of counting, a lot of

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:33.240
tabling, big figures. We use R Markdown. Something that we're excited to do is move

00:03:33.240 --> 00:03:38.360
the clinical trials reporting space more towards R, Python, other open source

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:45.160
technologies over traditionally a licensed dominated space, such as SAS and things like

00:03:45.160 --> 00:03:48.639
that. Of course, we're not, we're not the only kind of thought leaders in the space.

00:03:48.639 --> 00:03:53.639
There's a lot of great work from GSK, Roche and Taurus and others that we keep tabs on.

00:03:53.639 --> 00:03:55.600
And we love to learn from you all as we go.

00:03:57.479 --> 00:04:03.160
Thank you. And so I know a lot of people have commented in the chat already about your

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:07.960
amazing background and wanting to know, where are you right now?

00:04:10.479 --> 00:04:15.039
I've seen the guesses you're coming, Glacier National Park. Like I have, I feel like I've

00:04:15.039 --> 00:04:18.519
become Bigfoot these days. There was someone on Twitter recently said, did I just have a

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:24.119
Travis Gerke sighting? This, no, I'm not in Glacier anymore. We're now in Washington

00:04:24.119 --> 00:04:30.480
State. I'm on a river called the Nisqually, which is just outside of Olympia, near

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:36.559
Seattle. Awesome. So I guess I'm going to transition. No, I was going to say, I feel

00:04:36.559 --> 00:04:41.679
like that's a great transition into, I hinted that we would chat a little bit about very

00:04:41.679 --> 00:04:47.480
remote work and would love to learn a little bit more about your travels and working

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:52.399
remotely. Yeah, this is something kind of wild that we did. So my wife and we have two

00:04:52.399 --> 00:04:54.000
kids, they're seven and eight and a dog.

00:04:54.799 --> 00:04:58.839
We used to live in Florida and then we were never fans of the heat.

00:04:58.839 --> 00:05:02.480
And then for that and reasons, we just said, let's leave.

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:08.040
So so we sold our home and we bought an RV and a truck and sold most of our stuff.

00:05:08.040 --> 00:05:09.679
And now we live full time in an RV.

00:05:09.679 --> 00:05:14.000
And I just do data science from from wherever we are.

00:05:14.760 --> 00:05:17.679
Lately, it's been on the Pacific Northwest, but it's great.

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:21.160
I'm happy to answer any odd questions you might have about that.

00:05:21.480 --> 00:05:27.880
I 100 out of 10 recommend it if anyone has the urge to just get up and move.

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:29.679
It's very pandemic friendly.

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:32.799
We don't see many people often, although we want to go to the city.

00:05:32.799 --> 00:05:34.119
We can. We went to Seattle yesterday.

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:37.200
It was fun. So yeah, it's one of the good things about data science.

00:05:37.200 --> 00:05:38.920
It's pretty flexible. You can do from anywhere, really.

00:05:40.399 --> 00:05:45.760
That's amazing. I see, Libby, you asked a question somewhere a bit earlier about Internet.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:46.720
Do you want to jump in?

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:53.839
Yeah. Hey, Travis and I are talking about this on LinkedIn a little bit.

00:05:53.839 --> 00:05:57.239
I was like, you're going to spill all your secrets about how you have Internet and all

00:05:57.279 --> 00:06:02.000
these places, right, because I my husband and I both work remotely and we both feel

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:07.559
like the Internet is like a utility for us now, like a boundary to to working.

00:06:08.799 --> 00:06:12.040
So I'd love to know more about like how you stay connected all over the place.

00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:13.959
And if you have any trouble.

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:18.600
Yeah, no, I've I've shockingly actually not had any trouble yet.

00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:21.320
I geeked out on this big time before we did this, because you're right.

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:25.640
Without Internet, can't do much in terms of work.

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:31.279
But even in the remotest places we've been, I think Big Bend in Texas, we were the furthest

00:06:31.279 --> 00:06:33.000
from civilization.

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:36.799
I was still able to maintain Zoom meetings, much to my surprise.

00:06:36.799 --> 00:06:41.559
Actually, I prepped for a little bit on a week like that where I'm pretty remote.

00:06:41.559 --> 00:06:46.519
I make sure to set up a lot of kind of maybe it's a learning week or, you know, kind of

00:06:46.519 --> 00:06:48.720
heads down work. It's actually kind of good.

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:52.760
It gives you a little bit of space from the usual grind of just Zoom to Zoom.

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:55.399
But even in that case, it wasn't necessary.

00:06:55.399 --> 00:06:58.320
So today I'm using this hotspot.

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:01.959
So these hotspots, this one's the 5G Netgear.

00:07:02.399 --> 00:07:04.160
I can always share details about these things.

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:05.640
But this one.

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:10.000
So I have redundant phone plans for this sort of thing.

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:12.040
This one today, I'm on AT&T.

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:14.559
This hotspot also runs a T-Mobile.

00:07:14.559 --> 00:07:19.480
But I also have Verizon plans for it just depends.

00:07:19.480 --> 00:07:22.959
It depends where we are, what kind of service is going to give us the best.

00:07:22.959 --> 00:07:27.720
But I've actually never had a challenge streaming videos, Zoom, things like that.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:30.519
Something else that's helpful if you get a hotspot, these little boosters.

00:07:30.679 --> 00:07:32.079
This is like $20 on Amazon.

00:07:33.399 --> 00:07:34.880
They can be tremendously helpful.

00:07:35.839 --> 00:07:40.399
They kind of like funnel the signal into your hotspot a little bit better.

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:44.600
There is one. And if you want to really geek out on this, like I did, the best resources

00:07:44.839 --> 00:07:48.839
website called RVMobileInternet.com and you can check that out.

00:07:49.279 --> 00:07:53.559
These days, I think if I even had like a proper home, I might consider doing this instead

00:07:53.559 --> 00:07:58.480
of proper like cable or whatever internet, because the price is pretty similar.

00:07:58.480 --> 00:08:03.559
And often I have better signal much if I'm using it than my kind of at home

00:08:03.559 --> 00:08:05.480
colleagues that I'm Zooming with.

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:06.799
So it works well.

00:08:07.799 --> 00:08:09.959
It's fun. Did that answer your question?

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:12.320
I could really you can tell I can talk about that for days.

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:14.559
Yeah, no, it did.

00:08:14.559 --> 00:08:16.119
Thank you so much. I really appreciate it.

00:08:16.119 --> 00:08:17.720
I'm going to pass some of this along to my sister.

00:08:17.720 --> 00:08:19.000
My sister lived in a van.

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:21.279
Her and her husband lived in a van for about 10 years.

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:24.600
And they've just recently settled down into a tiny home.

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:27.320
But they are still really far from everything.

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:29.200
So it's been a little bit of a struggle.

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:35.520
Very cool. I love Raha's comment in the chat that this is exactly the kind of

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:37.119
conversation I've been craving.

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:40.919
Aaron, I see you asked a question, too.

00:08:40.919 --> 00:08:41.719
Do you want to jump in?

00:08:44.719 --> 00:08:46.000
Hi, this is Aaron.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:50.960
Um, I was just wondering, because I've tried to work in places where there's

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:56.919
lots of sunlight before, and I found it's really hard to, even if the sun

00:08:56.919 --> 00:09:02.080
isn't shining directly on you, if there is any sun touching anything in the

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:05.119
background behind you, it's hard to keep the glare off the screen.

00:09:05.119 --> 00:09:07.960
So I was wondering if you just had tips for us.

00:09:08.719 --> 00:09:12.719
I wish I had a brilliant thing to suggest and maybe others will.

00:09:13.479 --> 00:09:16.840
For today, I kind of just wandered around until I found a shady spot.

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:20.359
So I'm kind of like in the shade and I'm actually letting just

00:09:20.359 --> 00:09:21.760
my MacBook Pro do all the work.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:24.559
I'm even using the onboard camera.

00:09:24.640 --> 00:09:28.559
I mean, I do have, I do have like a stream cam that sometimes I use,

00:09:28.559 --> 00:09:30.679
but most times I find this is okay.

00:09:31.520 --> 00:09:33.479
I'm sorry if that's a disappointing answer.

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:36.520
No, thank you.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.960
I'm wishing I was wandering around outside, like looking for nice places

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:44.679
that I should just take the hangout outside next time.

