I see, Mike, that you asked a question in the chat.

00:09:48.919 --> 00:09:49.599
You want to jump in?

00:09:51.239 --> 00:09:52.080
Hi, thanks.

00:09:52.119 --> 00:09:53.919
Thanks for discussing this, Travis.

00:09:53.919 --> 00:09:56.640
I hope you don't mind that we're talking about, you know, your, your work

00:09:56.640 --> 00:10:00.039
lifestyle rather than data science or anything complicated.

00:10:00.039 --> 00:10:00.640
It's a hangout.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:01.520
That's what we're here for.

00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:05.799
So I, I work remote from the most of my team.

00:10:06.599 --> 00:10:13.520
They're predominantly US based and classic situation here in the, in the UK.

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:17.559
Today is a bank, a public holiday because of the Queen's Platinum Jubilee.

00:10:18.719 --> 00:10:22.359
Last Monday was a US public holiday.

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:26.960
So, you know, my colleagues are hitting me up on my public holiday, but I

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:30.400
wasn't allowed to hit them up on their public holiday, but when you're out

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:35.840
and about, how do your colleagues kind of, how do you, how do you balance

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:40.000
up, you know, time at work versus, you know, time I can be available for

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.479
conversations and how do you have those conversations with colleagues to say,

00:10:43.479 --> 00:10:47.960
look, you know, I'm going to be busy or traveling between here and here, you

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:51.200
know, so don't expect an answer in that time period.

00:10:51.919 --> 00:10:53.320
Yeah, it's such a great question.

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:57.200
And it is always, I mean, it's something that one has to be very intentional

00:10:57.200 --> 00:10:59.440
about and just communicate broadly.

00:10:59.719 --> 00:11:02.640
I do work very odd hours, especially now that I'm on West coast.

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:04.239
Most of my colleagues are on East coast time.

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:09.440
So I do try mostly to wake up very early and stick to their schedule,

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:11.119
but a lot of times it doesn't work out.

00:11:11.679 --> 00:11:12.440
And that's fine.

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:14.239
I'm kind of a night owl by nature anyway.

00:11:14.239 --> 00:11:19.080
So I will fire off emails at what is going to be like 2am Eastern.

00:11:19.359 --> 00:11:22.479
And what I do make sure to communicate is that, you know, if I'm, if I'm

00:11:22.479 --> 00:11:27.080
sending an email at 2am, like it doesn't mean I expect anyone to see or respond

00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:29.039
or do anything with that email at 2am.

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:33.320
Nor does it mean that I've been working from like 9am Eastern to 2am Eastern.

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:37.960
Like, it's just, you know, the, the async, I think, I mean, that's really

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:41.919
the future of most work environments for data science, I would suppose.

00:11:41.919 --> 00:11:45.479
I think someone like Chris Hurd on Twitter probably has stronger words

00:11:45.679 --> 00:11:48.159
than I do about that, but which, which I would recommend as a follow

00:11:48.159 --> 00:11:53.840
for remote work hot takes, but yeah, I mean, it's just, it's, it's

00:11:53.840 --> 00:11:55.239
really comes down to communication.

00:11:55.239 --> 00:11:57.440
I let people know I'm going to be traveling and, you know, blocking

00:11:57.440 --> 00:11:58.760
time on my calendar, things like that.

00:11:58.799 --> 00:12:02.359
Cause some afternoons I do, we do need to move or make it, make

00:12:02.359 --> 00:12:03.520
a drive or something like that.

00:12:03.520 --> 00:12:06.719
And, you know, I just, I just set it as busy and then people know that

00:12:06.719 --> 00:12:08.719
I'm, I'm not there and then just let them know.

00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:09.679
Thanks.

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:10.679
Yeah.

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:14.479
I think, I think blocking calendars is the, the, the key, right.

00:12:15.039 --> 00:12:17.760
Cause that says, you know, don't expect an answer in this three

00:12:17.760 --> 00:12:19.159
period, three hour period or whatever.

00:12:19.880 --> 00:12:20.119
Yep.

00:12:20.359 --> 00:12:20.760
For sure.

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:25.280
I like that point though, about you might answer it too, but that doesn't

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:28.440
mean you're expecting somebody to answer you right away too.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
It's when people answer back and you get into a conversation.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:38.520
It's Katie from our team used to put something in her email signature.

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:43.119
Like I send emails at off times, but that doesn't mean I expect a response.

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:44.599
Oh, that's great.

00:12:45.159 --> 00:12:45.559
I love that.

00:12:46.159 --> 00:12:49.640
Oh, I think I just, Sam, I think you just actually share that in the chat too.

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:56.239
Yeah, that was, we use that tagline a lot of my last job.

00:12:56.239 --> 00:12:58.559
In fact, our president had it on his email.

00:12:58.559 --> 00:12:59.799
I'm working on a remote schedule.

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:03.840
I know I don't expect an answer back and I'm flexible.

