I think a lot of us have learned in the last couple of years with the remote

00:15:20.039 --> 00:15:24.520
setups that, that really just the writing things down reduces those institutional

00:15:24.520 --> 00:15:28.640
knowledge silos, um, where you can never pick up if someone leaves and go

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:30.919
somewhere else and you go, Oh my God, we don't know how to do this anymore.

00:15:31.359 --> 00:15:35.239
Um, instead of the meetings whenever possible, writing things down is really

00:15:35.239 --> 00:15:38.960
wise, but as far as tooling, I, another one I wish I had a good answer for like,

00:15:38.960 --> 00:15:41.599
Oh, we use this consolidated approach with this thing, but now we're kind

00:15:41.599 --> 00:15:42.479
of spattered all over the place.

00:15:42.479 --> 00:15:46.599
We have some Slack, some teams, some GitHub emails.

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:48.000
Um, yeah, I don't know.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.200
Cause I, you know, I, I was, um, interacting with someone on tour

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:54.840
recently about loom, uh, and that looks awesome to sort of share it.

00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:59.039
So loom is a platform for sharing quick little videos, um, screen shares with

00:15:59.039 --> 00:16:02.239
like, I think it has like a little headshot of you talking in it or something

00:16:02.239 --> 00:16:06.359
like that, and it seems like a really great solution for asking and answering

00:16:06.359 --> 00:16:09.919
technical questions and in a streamlined way, but I have not used it myself.

00:16:09.960 --> 00:16:11.719
Curious if others have recommendations there.

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:13.280
Yeah.

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:17.359
And I see you said loom is great.

00:16:17.359 --> 00:16:18.799
I love to hear what that is.

00:16:19.679 --> 00:16:20.359
Yeah.

00:16:20.359 --> 00:16:26.200
So I've used it before for async work, especially with project kickoffs, when

00:16:26.200 --> 00:16:31.960
you can set context really easily with a short video, you can reduce meetings,

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.799
get everyone on the same page and then have everyone kind of digest all the

00:16:35.799 --> 00:16:39.559
information before you meet for more technical work.

00:16:39.799 --> 00:16:43.719
So I found that's really important whenever you're kicking off projects.

00:16:43.799 --> 00:16:48.200
Um, also for updates that you maybe would have a weekly sync on.

00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:52.200
Sometimes you can just do it in four minutes over a loom video.

00:16:52.200 --> 00:16:55.400
And then if there are any follow-up questions, someone could

00:16:55.400 --> 00:16:57.000
send you a loom video right back.

00:16:59.799 --> 00:17:00.400
Oh, I love it.

00:17:00.679 --> 00:17:01.080
Yeah.

00:17:02.359 --> 00:17:04.800
Anyone else have other tools that have been useful?

00:17:10.400 --> 00:17:14.000
I see a few being shared in the chat right now too.

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:17.319
Oh, Slack does the video messages.

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:17.800
I see.

00:17:17.880 --> 00:17:19.239
Um, Maddie said, that's awesome.

00:17:19.359 --> 00:17:19.959
I didn't know that.

