Um, I wanted to ask you about, um, your ability to work remotely.

00:17:40.119 --> 00:17:43.599
So is this something that you've always done or is it something that

00:17:43.599 --> 00:17:45.760
became possible because of the pandemic?

00:17:46.439 --> 00:17:50.479
And I'm also wondering, you know, I hear, I always hear a lot about how

00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:54.520
there's a lot of new roles that are opening that are remote, but I'm still

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:59.920
curious, is this like, are people hiring, um, with remote roles in mind

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:04.239
for data science, or is this still something that needs to be like negotiated?

00:18:04.640 --> 00:18:09.040
Um, like pretty intensely in order to have, cause I know there's a lot of

00:18:09.040 --> 00:18:13.760
talk now about return to work and, um, a lot of CEOs are saying people need to

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:17.640
come back, so I'm just curious, um, how this became possible for you and if

00:18:17.640 --> 00:18:21.239
you have any insight into what it maybe looks like now in the market.

00:18:22.079 --> 00:18:22.959
Yeah, sure.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.040
Um, so for like a couple of things there, that awesome question.

00:18:26.079 --> 00:18:26.479
I love it.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:31.319
The return to work phrase is like usually a hot button, um, phrase

00:18:31.319 --> 00:18:33.839
with huge remote proponents.

00:18:33.839 --> 00:18:39.160
Um, so it implies sort of that we weren't working before, like

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:40.160
when we aren't in the office.

00:18:40.199 --> 00:18:42.959
Um, I know that's not what you meant, but, um, but it's just sort of a

00:18:42.959 --> 00:18:44.680
funny thing that, that it, that it struck me.

00:18:44.719 --> 00:18:46.959
Um, but yeah, I think if it.

00:18:47.439 --> 00:18:51.359
In, in the negotiation stage, which you mentioned, um, so if you're looking

00:18:51.359 --> 00:18:57.040
at a role and, and it turns into a company or an org saying, well, we're

00:18:57.040 --> 00:19:01.359
going to let you work remote, um, as if it's some sort of privilege, it could

00:19:01.359 --> 00:19:06.199
be a red flag if, if remote really is your intention and your desired mode

00:19:06.199 --> 00:19:10.239
of working, and if you work well that way, it's just the way you work.

00:19:10.239 --> 00:19:12.640
I mean, I don't, I don't think it's, it's a, it's a privilege or not.

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:15.439
It's just, it's the way that you're productive.

00:19:15.439 --> 00:19:17.959
And if, and if orgs don't see it that way, then, then maybe that's

00:19:17.959 --> 00:19:20.800
a, that's kind of an early indicator.

00:19:20.839 --> 00:19:24.280
Um, so it's an important conversation to have early on, you know, like when,

00:19:24.319 --> 00:19:28.119
when we're interviewing new people for, for our team, we make sure to say

00:19:28.119 --> 00:19:31.959
like our org is a hundred percent remote, um, and indeed for us, and even

00:19:31.959 --> 00:19:35.560
for me, the a hundred percent remote, like going away remote only became

00:19:35.560 --> 00:19:36.959
possible because of the pandemic.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:41.079
Um, so kind of one of the few bright points of the pandemic, it allowed us to

00:19:41.079 --> 00:19:45.479
say, we really can do this from anywhere at any time, um, but now that we've done

00:19:45.479 --> 00:19:49.239
that and it's successful and there are of course, cost benefits to not having

00:19:49.239 --> 00:19:52.959
brick and mortar, uh, all those things, it makes sense for us.

00:19:52.959 --> 00:19:56.439
So we say like, you know, our intention is to stay a hundred percent remote

00:19:56.880 --> 00:19:57.959
and that's what this role is.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:01.280
And then there's no, there's no kind of like, we're gifting you this, this benefit.

00:20:01.319 --> 00:20:03.000
Um, it is just the way it is.

00:20:03.079 --> 00:20:06.160
Um, cause people are, I mean, a lot of studies I think lately are showing

00:20:06.160 --> 00:20:09.199
that people even became more productive when, when they work remotely, which

00:20:09.199 --> 00:20:09.880
makes a lot of sense to me.

00:20:09.880 --> 00:20:10.560
I know I did too.

00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:15.959
I don't waste two hours a day sitting in a car and, you know, putting on proper

00:20:16.239 --> 00:20:17.959
pants or whatever the case may be.

00:20:17.959 --> 00:20:18.199
Yeah.

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:19.119
Yeah.

00:20:19.119 --> 00:20:21.079
I definitely, um, I'm sorry.

00:20:21.079 --> 00:20:23.800
I definitely meant return to, uh, return to office, not return to work.

00:20:23.800 --> 00:20:25.319
Yeah, yeah, no, no, no, no.

00:20:25.599 --> 00:20:27.319
I didn't, I didn't mean to sound accused.

00:20:27.400 --> 00:20:29.359
No, I know exactly what you meant.

00:20:29.359 --> 00:20:31.599
I didn't, I didn't sense any like ill will there.

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:34.599
Um, but I definitely think you're right.

00:20:34.599 --> 00:20:37.160
I think that this pandemic has definitely shown that there are some

00:20:37.160 --> 00:20:40.199
things for data scientists that are just, I know I've personally found

00:20:40.199 --> 00:20:42.359
easier to do at home than in the office.

00:20:42.760 --> 00:20:45.520
Um, and I think this conversation we're having today is really bringing up

00:20:45.560 --> 00:20:48.959
important points about maybe some of the challenges with, with remote work.

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:53.839
Um, I know we're talking about loom and how that can be really helpful.

00:20:53.839 --> 00:20:56.920
I find another thing that still maybe I find more helpful in

00:20:56.920 --> 00:20:58.640
the office is brainstorming.

00:20:59.040 --> 00:21:02.800
And the main reason is because of whiteboarding it's, um, it's really hard

00:21:02.800 --> 00:21:06.239
to whiteboard over zoom and like brainstorm those ideas.

00:21:06.680 --> 00:21:11.359
Um, so thanks for having this conversation and for sharing, um, your insights.

00:21:12.239 --> 00:21:12.719
Yeah, sure.

00:21:12.959 --> 00:21:13.040
Yeah.

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:13.760
Thanks for the questions.

00:21:15.839 --> 00:21:18.680
I see there's an anonymous question that came in a bit earlier, which

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:20.079
is shifting gears a little bit.

00:21:20.119 --> 00:21:25.719
Um, but in simple terms, what is the difference between early phase

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:27.839
and late stage clinical trials?

00:21:28.199 --> 00:21:29.880
What's the difference in the work there?

00:21:30.680 --> 00:21:31.239
Oh, yeah.

00:21:31.280 --> 00:21:35.000
Um, sorry if I, I started with, if I started with jargon, um, this whole

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:36.640
thing, that was not what I meant to do.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:42.359
Um, so the, um, clinical trials as a whole, uh, have phase one,

00:21:42.359 --> 00:21:43.959
two, three, and sometimes four.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:49.199
Um, so phase one and two are kind of early investigational studies where

00:21:49.199 --> 00:21:51.439
you're looking at a new drug and you want to know, is it safe?

00:21:51.439 --> 00:21:55.160
And do we have any hints that it's going to be effective, um, for a particular

00:21:55.160 --> 00:22:01.079
disease or patient population and then later stage trials, um, or, uh, phase

00:22:01.079 --> 00:22:04.560
stage, um, the, the three, four.

00:22:04.599 --> 00:22:08.439
Um, so three is the, the classic randomized controlled trial where, where

00:22:08.439 --> 00:22:10.359
you're saying we believe it's safe.

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:11.319
We believe it's effective.

00:22:11.319 --> 00:22:11.959
Let's prove it.

00:22:12.319 --> 00:22:15.680
Um, and then a four is usually a very large population wide.

00:22:15.760 --> 00:22:19.800
Um, you kind of surveil the, the, you know, like lots of people

00:22:19.800 --> 00:22:21.000
are taking statins these days.

00:22:21.520 --> 00:22:23.640
You could run a phase four or something like a statin and make sure that it's

00:22:23.640 --> 00:22:27.319
doing what it's supposed to do and that it's still safe and, and, um, larger

00:22:27.319 --> 00:22:31.599
populations, sometimes even harder to reach, um, aspects of the population

00:22:31.599 --> 00:22:34.839
that might not have enrolled in the classic phase three RCT.

00:22:35.239 --> 00:22:41.040
Um, and then, uh, I was, I was referring to late stage, um, prostate cancer.

00:22:41.079 --> 00:22:44.880
Um, prostate cancer is a disease in which, um, a lot of men are diagnosed

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:50.280
very early on, so an early stage of disease, um, and the, the kind of

00:22:50.280 --> 00:22:54.239
actions you would take clinically for early stage prostate cancer are very

00:22:54.239 --> 00:22:56.920
different than those you would take for late stage prostate cancer, which is

00:22:56.920 --> 00:22:59.560
most often test the size to the bone or other places.

00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:03.800
So we mostly operate in the, in the late stage, um, phase with, um, metastatic

00:23:03.800 --> 00:23:08.680
disease, um, kind of low life expectancy and, and a real opportune time to

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:10.800
introduce new drugs that are helpful.

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:14.359
Thank you, Travis.

00:23:14.359 --> 00:23:15.160
That's really helpful.

00:23:16.040 --> 00:23:16.239
Sure.

00:23:16.839 --> 00:23:22.119
Um, a few other questions in the chat coming in right now too.

00:23:22.119 --> 00:23:26.239
And, um, I see Sam, you asked one and you put a little star for me to read it.

00:23:26.239 --> 00:23:30.640
So a reminder, if you maybe are somewhere that's a bit loud or you want me to read

00:23:30.640 --> 00:23:34.199
a question, feel free to put a star next to it in the chat too.

00:23:34.920 --> 00:23:39.640
Um, but it was, how do you convince leadership in pharma companies that are

00:23:39.640 --> 00:23:45.239
still hesitant or resistant toward remote work, that it's the future for data science?

00:23:47.880 --> 00:23:51.199
Um, oh, that's like the million dollar question, I guess.

00:23:51.199 --> 00:23:55.920
I, um, I suppose I've been fortunate not to be in that role.

00:23:55.920 --> 00:23:58.359
I've had to make that, I've not been in a position where I've had

00:23:58.359 --> 00:23:59.800
to make that argument myself.

00:23:59.839 --> 00:24:07.599
Um, so I'm gonna, I'm gonna cast an, I don't know, into the, into the, um, into

00:24:07.640 --> 00:24:11.520
the chat, uh, if anyone has suggestions, I'm, I'm really interested to hear them.

00:24:11.520 --> 00:24:14.880
I read a lot of blogs and a lot of kind of like Twitter takes on this.

00:24:14.959 --> 00:24:19.680
Um, and you know, like some of the hot takes are just sort of like, well, I'll

00:24:19.680 --> 00:24:22.760
leave, you know, we'll, we'll leave and go get remote jobs that make more money.

00:24:22.760 --> 00:24:24.400
And I mean, like, sure.

00:24:24.439 --> 00:24:28.079
Um, but if you like the work you're doing and the place you're, you're working,

00:24:28.079 --> 00:24:30.319
that's probably not the best solution.

00:24:30.359 --> 00:24:34.839
Um, if you'd like to, you know, have a civil, productive conversation.

00:24:34.959 --> 00:24:35.160
I.

00:24:36.400 --> 00:24:39.239
Has anyone had to make this case or wanted?

00:24:40.079 --> 00:24:44.040
Yeah, it'd be great if someone, yeah, someone has a suggestion or experience.

00:24:44.359 --> 00:24:53.119
So in, um, in my experience, kind of in a previous role, um, we did have a group

00:24:53.160 --> 00:25:00.439
that we're working together, um, in one location and in that sense, we, there

00:25:00.439 --> 00:25:04.160
were certain individuals, this is pre pandemic, but certain individuals can,

00:25:04.359 --> 00:25:10.839
in order to get work-life balance and right, and, you know, kind of get that in

00:25:10.839 --> 00:25:16.239
place where they were having to commute a fair distance and take kids to school.

00:25:16.239 --> 00:25:21.239
And so their, their work day was kind of difficult because of all of that.

00:25:21.239 --> 00:25:24.640
They, they were trying to make the point that perhaps it would be more productive

00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:28.880
for them to be at home certain days in the week so that they could then, you

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:33.719
know, get the kids off to school, do a full day's work, go back, pick them up.

00:25:33.719 --> 00:25:35.239
And deal with everything.

00:25:36.199 --> 00:25:41.880
The line manager at the time was kind of saying, well, because they wanted to

00:25:41.880 --> 00:25:47.359
keep a cohesive group present in that location, if individuals were kind of

00:25:47.359 --> 00:25:49.479
off working in remote locations, that was harder.

00:25:51.119 --> 00:25:55.880
I can kind of understand that rationale just in terms of a group dynamic and

00:25:56.040 --> 00:26:04.599
the kind of over the coffee pot, you know, round the kettle kind of discussions that

00:26:04.599 --> 00:26:08.479
you occasionally have with colleagues, or, you know, you just turn around in your

00:26:08.479 --> 00:26:12.040
chair and ask questions, that's much harder when everyone's remote.

00:26:12.800 --> 00:26:17.359
So I kind of understood that point of view.

00:26:18.640 --> 00:26:25.160
I think, well, just before the pandemic, I made the case to work remote and, you

00:26:25.160 --> 00:26:28.280
know, my manager at the time was like, sure, you know, you're, you're on the

00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:31.719
phone 90% of the time to folks in a remote location.

00:26:31.719 --> 00:26:33.239
So why should it matter where you work?

00:26:33.959 --> 00:26:37.680
And then the pandemic happened.

00:26:38.199 --> 00:26:44.000
And as far as I'm, as far as I'm aware, I don't think that productivity has

00:26:44.079 --> 00:26:49.199
markedly dropped within my organisation in the last two years.

00:26:49.239 --> 00:26:54.479
So I think it's a much stronger lever now to say, hey, look, we can do this

00:26:54.479 --> 00:27:01.119
remotely. Sure, there are some jobs that are more tricky, or certain circumstances

00:27:01.119 --> 00:27:06.280
that are, you know, maybe you need to have closer interactions with colleagues.

00:27:06.839 --> 00:27:11.560
Like if someone is brand new into the industry from graduating, you know, you

00:27:11.560 --> 00:27:14.760
maybe want to have closer interactions with them to make sure that they're getting

00:27:14.760 --> 00:27:20.479
it and they're not kind of, you know, veering off the path too much, let's, let's

00:27:20.479 --> 00:27:27.520
call it that. But I honestly think that once you kind of get to a level of knowing

00:27:27.520 --> 00:27:34.000
what you're doing in your job, I can't see why anyone could have a strong argument

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:35.599
that you have to be in the office.

00:27:38.800 --> 00:27:44.920
Yeah, that's a great, I love that story in that you're pushing for pre-pandemic.

00:27:44.920 --> 00:27:49.079
And I think for a lot of places, the pandemic just was the proof that said, look, we

00:27:49.079 --> 00:27:54.680
really can do this. And like, you know, it's, it's, it's almost like the onus is now

00:27:54.680 --> 00:27:59.640
on the, the in-office people like, well, show me how productivity increases when we're

00:27:59.640 --> 00:28:05.000
in the office. Cause we've, we've, we've proved it like in, in the most dire of

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:08.719
circumstances, like in a time when we shouldn't have been productive.

00:28:09.119 --> 00:28:13.800
I mean, that's the thing that the COVID enforced remote style of remote work is not

00:28:13.800 --> 00:28:14.920
normal remote work.

00:28:14.959 --> 00:28:16.520
That's not the way that it's supposed to be.

00:28:16.800 --> 00:28:21.079
It's supposed to be more of a choice and a, you know, an intentional thought process than

00:28:21.079 --> 00:28:23.319
rather than a, than an emergency knee-jerk reaction.

00:28:24.199 --> 00:28:29.119
So that we did so many companies that so well remotely in, in the worst of situations means

00:28:29.119 --> 00:28:31.119
that they'll do even better in normal times.

00:28:32.880 --> 00:28:37.199
I mean, I, I have to say that I think communication is much more difficult.

00:28:37.760 --> 00:28:40.239
You know, you have to be intentional about communication.

00:28:40.839 --> 00:28:49.920
And also I think that it's easy for individuals to feel isolated, you know, and

00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:52.839
that's, that's got a knock-on effect on mental health and everything else.

00:28:52.839 --> 00:28:56.280
So, you know, I, there are pros and cons for sure.

00:28:56.839 --> 00:29:02.680
But, you know, I think having those honest discussions about them is, is good first

00:29:02.680 --> 00:29:02.880
step.

00:29:03.719 --> 00:29:04.920
Yeah, totally agree.

00:29:04.959 --> 00:29:09.199
I, something I meant to mention about remote work in general, I learned a lot from the

00:29:09.199 --> 00:29:12.400
GitLab suite of resources.

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:13.800
They have so much out there.

00:29:13.800 --> 00:29:15.640
I mean, they have a really good Coursera course.

00:29:15.920 --> 00:29:20.520
I think it's called remote team management or something like this, which is very good.

00:29:20.520 --> 00:29:25.719
And then they have a remote team handbook, which speaks to a lot of those topics.

00:29:25.719 --> 00:29:30.520
You know, how do we, they always say the biggest, you know, challenge is communication

00:29:30.520 --> 00:29:33.280
and, you know, document everything, but that's really hard.

00:29:33.280 --> 00:29:36.199
And how do you carve time for it and make sure it's done?

00:29:36.359 --> 00:29:39.680
And how do we balance just kind of connectedness in the long run?

00:29:39.719 --> 00:29:42.280
Certainly things to think about and be intentional about.

00:29:44.040 --> 00:29:46.560
Oh, I saw, yeah, that's the one, remote team management.

00:29:46.599 --> 00:29:47.359
That's the right one.

00:29:47.439 --> 00:29:47.800
Okay.

00:29:47.880 --> 00:29:48.079
Yeah.

